<seg id=1> The UN's Latin American and Caribbean Areas Economic Committee estimated that the economic growth in that area would drop by 1% next year. </seg>
<seg id=2> But the organization admitted that the situation might be even worse. </seg>
<seg id=3> Now listen to the following further report by our VOA reporter Michael in South America section. Tian Ye reads the report. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> According to the prelimilary observation, the economic growth rate of this year in Latin American and Caribbean areas will be 2.3%, which has dropped rapidly compared with 5.2% of last year. </seg>
<seg id=5> If it had not been for the strong economic operation during the first half of the year, the number would have been much smaller. </seg>
<seg id=6> The committee said that although there were external turmoils, the economy in this area still keeps relatively good growth. </seg>
<seg id=7> But the worst influence has now shown up, and will continue until next year. </seg>
<seg id=8> The UN Economic Committee said that the hard economic situation in Brazil was reflected in the countries in the southern cone-shaped area. </seg>
<seg id=9> These countries were mostly influenced by the low prices of the staple export products. </seg>
<seg id=10> The Committee said that most countries chose to raise the interest rate in order to protect their currencies. </seg>
<seg id=11> This kind of measure had restrained the economic growth and made the unemployment rate go up. </seg>
<seg id=12> The report said that if these countries wanted to maintain their stronger competitiveness by devaluation, they would risk worse inflation, ... </seg>
